<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1400,2038]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
Five additional specimens from the 
<typeStatus box="[604,652,1762,1786]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">type</typeStatus>
locality are deposited in the laboratory of I. Ribera (IBE – Institut de Biología Evolutiva, Barcelona, 
<collectingCountry box="[507,576,1797,1822]" name="Spain" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Spain</collectingCountry>
). The soft tissue from a single specimen was digested and the DNA isolated and stored in the DNA collection with voucher number IBE-RA 
<number box="[894,937,1834,1858]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" value="744.0">744</number>
. The extracted specimen is kept in the IBE with the same reference number.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1400,2038]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,465,1905,1930]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<number box="[476,509,1906,1930]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" value="1.8">1.8</number>
–2.0 mm long. Habitus and coloration as in 
<figureCitation box="[1033,1103,1905,1930]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[184,1415,217,1871]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,195,1887]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Ochthebius hivae, habitus, paratype from Khairabad River; scale: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218204/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
Fig. 
<number box="[1088,1103,1906,1930]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
. Externally, the new species resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[270,461,1941,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Ochthebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="khuzestanicus">
<emphasis box="[270,461,1941,1965]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<collectingCountry box="[270,293,1942,1965]" name="Iceland" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">O</collectingCountry>
. khuzestanicus
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingCountry box="[475,523,1942,1966]" name="Iran" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Iran</collectingCountry>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Jach &amp; Delgado" authorityName="Jach &amp; Delgado" box="[586,907,1941,1966]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Ochthebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wurayah">
<emphasis box="[586,606,1942,1965]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<collectingCountry box="[586,606,1942,1965]" name="Iceland" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">O</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[620,718,1941,1965]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">wurayah</emphasis>
Jäch &amp; Delgado
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingCountry box="[922,986,1942,1966]" name="United Arab Emirates" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">UAE</collectingCountry>
). It differs from these species in the less coarsely granulate elytra, and from 
<taxonomicName box="[580,777,1977,2001]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Ochthebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="khuzestanicus">
<emphasis box="[580,777,1977,2001]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<collectingCountry box="[580,603,1978,2001]" name="Iceland" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">O</collectingCountry>
. khuzestanicus
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also in the less densely punctate pronotum. Head and pronotum of 
<taxonomicName box="[297,391,2013,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Ochthebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hivae">
<emphasis box="[297,317,2014,2037]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<collectingCountry box="[297,317,2014,2037]" name="Iceland" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">O</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[331,391,2013,2037]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">hivae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually more distinctly cupreous than in the two other species.
</paragraph>
